I was introduced to this recipe by a friend, and just had to have it myself, and have passed it on since. Since my husband isn't huge on fish but loves clams, I took BootedBear's suggestion and replaced the fish with 3 cans of baby clams (for a doubled recipe). There was more than enough clam juice from those to supply the recipe's needs, and this made a fantastic clam chowder!

Rating: 4
This is one of my favorite recipes and I make it frequently, always with RAVE REVIEWS! We are not meat eaters so we omit the bacon and add a little extra garlic, some leeks, and extra celery. We have so much wonderful seafood to choose from, we often add something new. My favorite is fresh grouper and sometimes some bay scallops. Frozen baby corn or fresh corn is a nice addition as well.This recipe doubles and triples well. Try it, you'll love it!

Rating: 4
I don't eat bacon or shellfish (including clams), so I used 1 Tbs. olive oil, 2 Tbs. butter and 1 clove of garlic, minced, to saute the onions to make up for the flavor that bacon drippings would have given the dish. I used 2 cups of chicken broth instead of the clam juice and water. Then I used 1 cup regular CoffeeMate and 1 cup of 1% milk instead of the heavy cream and the chowder tasted very rich and creamy without the calories. And then because I had more liquid than the original recipe called for, I added the kernels from 1 ear of fresh corn. I am originally from Boston and was raised on chowders, and this rendition was excellent! I would definitely make it again.

